TY  - JOUR
T1  - Research Notes. Getting More Than You Pay For: Organizational Citizenship Behavior and Pay-For-Performance Plans
AU  - Deckop, John R.
AU  - Mangel, Robert
AU  - Cirka, Carol C.
Y1  - 1999/08/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/257012
DO  - 10.5465/257012
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 420
EP  - 428
VL  - 42
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Economic control frameworks such as agency theory start with the assumption that employee and employer interests naturally diverge, whereas alternative control frameworks imply that employee and employer interests are often aligned. Integrating these literatures, we hypothesized that value alignment moderates the impact of pay for performance on extrarole behaviors. Our study of employees in the utility industry supported this hypothesis. Pay for performance had a negative impact on extrarole behaviors for employees low in value alignment but not for employees high in value alignment.
AB  - Economic control frameworks such as agency theory start with the assumption that employee and employer interests naturally diverge, whereas alternative control frameworks imply that employee and employer interests are often aligned. Integrating these literatures, we hypothesized that value alignment moderates the impact of pay for performance on extrarole behaviors. Our study of employees in the utility industry supported this hypothesis. Pay for performance had a negative impact on extrarole behaviors for employees low in value alignment but not for employees high in value alignment.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/257012
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/257012
Y2  - 2026/04/24
